2026-04-16 12:37:30 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module PCB (relay switched contact trace)'] hypothesis_explanation="Despite all nominal voltage essentially making it to the relay's switched contact output terminal, the voltage at the external output terminals of the control module (measured both with and without the load connected) remains stuck at ~0.36V and not at 12V as it should be when the relay is closed. There is confirmed continuity (0.01 Ω) between the relay output and Control Output Cable (+), yet the voltage at this terminal does not match. This suggests the possibility of a highly resistive, partially open or corroded PCB trace or solder joint at or immediately downstream of the relay switched contact. The resistance is enough to pass a continuity test but not enough to allow any significant current (even unloaded) to pass the supply voltage. Therefore, the fault is most likely a high-resistance fault in the PCB, via, or solder joint for the relay switched contact area within the control module."
